(31, 'International Webinar  Living with Uncertainty, Sustainable Coastal Area & River Basin Management in Indonesia: Past, Present and Future', 'international-webinar--living-with-uncertainty-sustainable-coastal-area--river-basin-management-in-i', '<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Trebuchet MS,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"line-height:207%\">Indonesia, the largest archipelago in the world, has 17,508 islands, of which about 6000 are inhabited with a total coastline length of 54,720 km (The World Factbook), 3rd longest in the world. Indonesian coasts are highly populated with around 100km of the coast is inhabited by 200 million people. 150 millions of them rely on marine resources for their livelihood (WRI, 2001). Anthropogenic activities are one of the main causes of coastal environmental degradation such as coastal erosion, coastal flooding, subsidence of lowland and wetland areas, and increasing water salinity. Coastal erosion, as reported by the Ministry of Maritime Affairs and Fisheries, Indonesia loses around 1,950 ha annually due to erosion. While in the last 15 years, the total loss of coastal areas is 29,261ha, about the same size as Jakarta. Land conversion from mangrove to fishpond worsened the erosion. Central Java, East Java, and Southeast Sulawesi are the three most affected regions. An extreme example, erosion along the western coast of Demak, Central Java, has caused three villages to sink into the sea. These environmental damages, indeed, has made the coast more vulnerable. As coasts are home to more than 77% population, actions should be made in the light of providing a sustainable solution in the form of integrated coastal zone management (ICZM). </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><span style=\"font-family:Trebuchet MS,Helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"line-height:207%\">Water Resources Engineering Universitas Brawijaya (WRE-UB), with its long history in water education, has attention to contribute to Indonesian coastal development. As part of the contribution we are organizing an international webinar by learning from world-renowned scientist, policy maker-regulator (Ministry of Public Works and Housing), and water manager-professional (state-owned company Perum Jasa Tirta 1). We understand that solving coastal zone issues cannot be done only by looking at the lowland, but should also include hinterland. Hence, we can have a holistic understanding and contribute to Indonesian coastal development and management as scholars. Solutions are not generic, they are tailored and unique to every geographic condition. With its many interesting coastal features and river basin, Indonesia can, in the future, contribute to the science and lead the research and invention in coastal engineering. However, this can be achieved by active and good collaboration from many different sectors.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; text-align: justify;\"><img alt=\"Poster Webinar\" src=\"https://pengairan-brawijaya.herokuapp.com/asset/foto/Salinan_Seminar_Internasional.jpg\" style=\"width: 1200px; height: 1698px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 8pt; text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><b><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FNFavuxITfs&amp;feature=youtu.be\">YouTube Streaming</a></span></b></p>\r\n', 'Live on YouTube', '', 'perokok1.jpg', 'N', '2020-10-24', '2020-10-24', '2020-10-23', '-', 0, 'superadmin'),
